2. An electrical manufacturing company conducts quality checks at specified periods on the products it manufactures. Historically, the failure rate for the manufactured item is 5%. Suppose a random sample of 10 manufactured items is selected. Answer the following questions. [4 Marks] ¶

2.A. Probability that none of the items are defective? [1 Mark] ¶

In [4]:
# To solve this problem , we can use the binomial distribution formula which is as follows:

# P(X = 0) = (n choose x) * p^x * (1 - p)^(n - x)

# where

# n = 10 (sample size)
# x = 0 (number of defective items, here we have none of the product is defective so x =0)
# p = 0.05 (probability of an item being defective ,which is failure rate of for the manufactured item.)

# We solve this using Python code, python's scipy library provides us the binom.pmf() function, which helps to calculate the probablity mass function of the binomial distribution.

# Below is python code:


from scipy.stats import binom

n = 10  #  this is sample size
p = 0.05  

# Calculate the probability using binom.pmf()
probability = binom.pmf(0, n, p)

# Print the result
print("The probability that none of the items are defective:", probability)

The probability that none of the items are defective: 0.5987369392383787

Thus , we get the probability of None of the 10 item are defective = 0.5987 ( approximately = 0.6 or 60 %.) ¶

2.B. Probability that exactly one of the items is defective? [1 Mark]¶

In [5]:
# Ans: 

# In this example also , we use the binomial distribution function :

# Here, we have to find the probability when exactly one item is defective.

# so , X=1

# We solve this problem using the python code , which is as follow 


from scipy.stats import binom

n = 10  # this is our sample size
p = 0.05  # this is probability of defect (failure)

# Calculate the probability using binom.pmf()

probability = binom.pmf(1, n, p)


print("The probability of having exactly one of the items defective is :", probability)

The probability of having exactly one of the items defective is : 0.3151247048623047

Thus , we get the probability of exactly having 10 item defective is = 0.3151 or 31.51 % ¶

2.C. Probability that two or fewer of the items are defective? [1 Mark] ¶

# For that we use cumulative distribution function from scipy library's binom distribution .

# Below is python code:


from scipy.stats import binom

n = 10  # this is sample size

3. A car salesman sells on an average 3 cars per week. [3 Marks] ¶

3.A. What is Probability that in a given week he will sell some cars? [1 Mark] ¶

In [8]:
'''Ans: 

In this example ,our problem statement is to find the probability that salesman will sell some cars in given week means we need to determine the probability of selling at least one car.

Note: We can use the Poisson distribution when we know the average rate of an event occurring over a fixed interval of time.
So , To solve this example , we use the Poisson distribution ,

Average no. of cars sold per week is given as 3 .

In this example , we have given the average rate so we use Poisson distribution.

the no. of cars sold follows a Poisson distribution with lambda value as 3.

Note: Here , we can use the complementary rule , i.e
The probability of selling at least one car can be calculated as the complement of the probability of selling zero cars.

P(selling at least one car) = 1 - P(selling zero cars)

We solve this using python code which is as follows:
we can use the scipy library's poisson.pmf() function , which calculates the probability mass function of Poisson distribution.'''




from scipy.stats import poisson

avg_cars_sold = 3

# Calculate the probability using poisson.pmf()

probability = 1 - poisson.pmf(0, avg_cars_sold) # we are using the complementary rule , so we minused it from 1.


# Print the result
print("The probability of selling some cars in a given week:", probability)

The probability of selling some cars in a given week: 0.950212931632136

Thus , probability of salesman will sell some cars in a given week is approximately 0.9502 or 95.02% ¶

3.B. What is Probability that in a given week he will sell 2 or more but less than 5 cars? [1 Mark]¶

In [9]:
'''
Ans: 

Here, we again use the Poisson distribution.

In this case, the average number of cars sold per week is given as 3.

We want to calculate the probability of selling 2 or more but less than 5 cars in a week.

For that , we have to utilize the scipy library's poisson.cdf() function, which calculates the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of the Poisson distribution.

Python code is as follow :

'''


from scipy.stats import poisson

avg_cars_sold = 3

# Calculate the probability using poisson.cdf()

prob_less_tn_5 = poisson.cdf(4, avg_cars_sold)

prob_less_tn_2 = poisson.cdf(1, avg_cars_sold)

probability = prob_less_tn_5 - prob_less_tn_2

# Print the result
print("The probability of selling 2 or more but less than 5 cars in a given week:", probability)

The probability of selling 2 or more but less than 5 cars in a given week: 0.6161149710523164

Thus, the probability that the car salesman will sell 2 or more but less than 5 cars in a given week is approximately 0.6161 or 61.61%. ¶

3.C. Plot the poisson distribution function for cumulative probability of cars sold per-week vs number of cars sold per week. [1 Mark] ¶

Ans: ¶

In [10]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.stats import poisson # we have to import the poisson function which is in scipy.stats module.

lambda_val = 3  # Average number of cars sold per week

x = np.arange(0, 11)  # Number of cars sold per week (from 0 to 10)
cumulative_prob = poisson.cdf(x, lambda_val)  # Cumulative probability

plt.figure(figsize=(11,7))
plt.plot(x, cumulative_prob, 'go--', label='Poisson Distribution')
plt.xlabel('No. of Cars Sold per Week',fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Probability',fontsize=14)
plt.title('Poisson Distribution for Cars Sold per Week',fontsize=18)
plt.xticks(np.arange(11))
plt.legend(fontsize=20,loc=5)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

4. Accuracy in understanding orders for a speech based bot at a restaurant is important for the Company X which has designed, marketed and launched the product for a contactless delivery due to the COVID-19 pandemic. Recognition accuracy that measures the percentage of orders that are taken correctly is 86.8%. Suppose that you place an order with the bot and two friends of yours independently place orders with the same bot. Answer the following questions. [3 Marks] .¶

4.A. What is the probability that all three orders will be recognised correctly? [1 Mark] ¶

In [11]:
'''
Ans: 
We can solve this problem by using the binomial distribution.

In this example , we need to find the probability that all three orders will be recognized correctly.

Binomial Distribution Formula is:
P(X = k) = (n choose k) * p^k * (1 - p)^(n - k)

where:
n = number of trials means total number of orders given to bot to recognize. (in this case, 3)
k = number of successes means bot identified orders correctly (in this case, 3)
p = probability of success which is given recognition probability = 0.868

We solve this using Python code, python's scipy library provides us the binom.pmf() function, which helps to calculate the probablity mass function of the binomial distribution.

'''


from scipy.stats import binom


p=0.868   # P -->  accuracy of recognition.
n=3       # They are total 3 persons, each can put one order so n --> = 3
k=3       # No. of orders we have given to bot to recognize.



prob = binom.pmf(k, n, p)

print(prob)

print('*'* 40)
print("Probability that all three orders will be recognized correctly by bot is :", prob )

0.653972032
****************************************
Probability that all three orders will be recognized correctly by bot is : 0.653972032

Thus , the probability that all three orders will be recognized correctly by the bot, using the binomial distribution, is 0.6539 or 65.39%. ¶

4.B. What is the probability that none of the three orders will be recognised correctly? [1 Mark] ¶

In [12]:
'''
Ans: 
Our problem statement state that the probability that none of the three orders will be recognized correctly , so we need to consider each order as a failure (not recognized correctly) and probability of that each failure will be (1 - 0.868) = 0.132.
we use here the binomial distribution formula,

We solve this problem using the python code which is as bellow :

'''


from scipy.stats import binom


p=0.132   # P -->  probability of not recognized correctly which is ( 1- recognized correctly)=(1-0.868)=0.132.
n=3       # They are total 3 persons, each can put one order so n --> = 3
k=3       # No. of orders recognized incorrectly .

prob = binom.pmf(k, n, p)

print("Probability that none of the three orders will be recognized correctly :", prob)

Probability that none of the three orders will be recognized correctly : 0.0022999680000000003

Thus, the probability that none of the three orders will be recognized correctly by the bot, using the binomial distribution, is approximately 0.0023 or 0.23%.¶

'''

From the problem statement , we need to calculate the probability of at least two of the three orders will be recognized correctly ,

so will use the binomial distribution to calculate these probabilities.

First , we calculate the probabilities of having two and three successful orders individually and then sum up them .

Python's stats library provides binomial function so we use that function to solve this problem.

'''



from scipy.stats import binom

p=0.868 # Probability of recognizing correctly.
k=2     # Number of orders recognized correclty.

print("********************************")

p=0.868 # Probability of recognizing correctly.
k=3     # Number of orders recognized correclty.
n=3     # Total no. of orders given to recognize. 

prob_3_correct = binom.pmf(k, n, p)
print(prob_3_correct)

print("******************************************")
print("Probability that at least two of the three orders will be recognized correctly is :",prob_2_correct + prob_3_correct )

5. Explain 1 real life industry scenario (other than the ones mentioned above) where you can use the concepts learnt in this module of Applied Statistics to get data driven business solution. [3 Marks] ¶

Ans: ¶

  • In Banking sector , identifying the total number of fraudulent transactions occurring within particular area and within particular time frame is very important parameter in whole business life cycle of that particular bank .
  • We can use the binomial distribution which will help to predict the number of fraud transactions that might occur on the following day or in the future.
  • First , we should consider the assumption in binomial distribution before using the function for that particular problem statement.

Binomial distribution has following assumption so we will compare them with this banking sector scenario:¶

  1. Fixed number of transactions :

    While using the binomial distribution , there should be fixed number of transactions. So, in this banking sector scenario we have fixed number of transactions which we can check for fraud or not. Thus, this banking sector scenario satisfy our first assumption.

  1. Binary outcomes:

    In banking transaction , we only get the two output i.e transaction is fraud and not fraud, thus these outcome satisfy the second assumption of binomial distribution i.e out come should be in binary format.

  1. Independent trials:

    Here in this scenario also , each transaction is independent of one another meaning outcome of one transaction does not affect the outcome of another transaction thus this assumption is also satisfied.

  1. Constant probability of success:

    While using the Binomial distribution , probability of success should remain constant for each trial. So , we can set the probability of success of identifying the fraud transaction to a particular number . Thus, this assumption is also satisfied.

Thus, all the assumption of the Binomial distribution are satisfied by the example of banking sector. So, we can easily use the Binomial distribution to identify that the transaction is fraud or not fraud.¶

We will explain this banking sector scenario with one example:¶

A bank wants to examine that within a sample of debit card transactions, what is the probability of detecting a certain number of fraud transactions. Bank has historical data , which indicates that bank has overall fraud rate of debit card transactions as 0.2%(0.002) .¶

  • Now bank wants to determine the probability of detecting 10 fraud transaction from the given sample of 10,000 debit cards.
  • To calculate this probability , we have binomial distribution function of which all the assumptions are satisfied by the baking example.
  • python's stats library provides this in build's in function of binomial distribution , so we use it as bellow:
In [14]:
from scipy.stats import binom

# Given values are:

# n --> sample_size = 10000
# p --> fraud_rate = 0.002
# k --> num_fraud_detected = 10

# probability = binom.pdf(k, n,p )


probability = binom.pmf(10, 10000,0.002 )


print("Probability of detecting 10 fraudulent transactions in the sample is :", probability)

Probability of detecting 10 fraudulent transactions in the sample is : 0.00579014500751495

Thus, Probability of detecting 10 fraudulent transactions in the sample is approximately 0.0058 or 0.58 %.

Thus , we see that how binomial function helps banks to identify **how likely it is that a certain number of fraudulent transactions will occur in a given day within a certain volume of transactions. By setting appropriate thresholds and monitoring deviations from the expected distribution, banks can easily identify potential fraud transaction patterns and can take preventive measures on time to avoid huge loss to bank.**¶

We will check the symmetry of the data distribution using df.skew() function.¶

Information about skewness :¶

The skewness values indicate the degree of asymmetry in the distribution of data.¶

  • If the skewness value is close to 0, the distribution is approximately symmetric.

  • If the skewness value is negative, the distribution is left-skewed or negatively skewed, with a longer left tail.

  • And , If the skewness value is positive, the distribution is right-skewed or positively skewed, with a longer right tail.

Q.3. Please include any improvements or suggestions to the association management on quality, quantity, variety, velocity, veracity etc. on the data points collected by the association to perform a better data analysis in future. At-least 1 suggestion for each point. [10 Marks] ¶

Ans: ¶

1.Quality:¶

  • Data set contains some incomplete teams information. Example: Team61 don't have information for many columns like Score, PlayedGames, WonGames, DrawnGames, LostGames, BasketScored, BasketGiven etc. Also name of Runner up column has not same format as others all have.
  • Quality in data analysis means the accuracy, completeness, consistency, and reliability of the data being analyzed. Improving data quality helps for obtaining reliable and meaningful results.

Association can follow some below approaches to improve data quality.:¶

  1. Data validation and verification: This step involves validating data at the point of entry or during data processing, checking for completeness, and identifying any outliers or inconsistencies.

  2. Data cleansing and preprocessing: For this , Association management can utilize techniques such as data imputation, outliers detection, or duplication. This will help to Association for ensuring transparency and clarity regarding the data's characteristics, origins, and transformations.

  3. Data documentation and metadata management: It includes information about the data's source, structure, and meaning.

  4. Regular data quality assessment: Conducting regular assessments of data quality to monitor its accuracy, completeness, and consistency, can help Association management to identify and address any issues promptly, ensuring the reliability of the data used for analysis.

Thus , above steps will help Association to enhance the quality of their data, leading to more accurate and trustworthy insights in data analysis.

2. Quantity: ¶

  • Quantity refers to the volume or amount of data available for analysis.

  • Given Data set has only information of 61 teams which is not enough. To improve the data set quantity , association management can add players information , so that by analyzing the each player ability , association can analyze data well and can predict insights with more probability.

For improving quantity , Association can consider the following strategies:¶

  1. Data collection expansion: This can be done by collecting data from additional sources, expanding the timeframe of data collection, or including a larger sample size in surveys or experiments.

  2. Data augmentation and synthesis: This can be done by merging data from different sources, incorporating publicly available datasets, or leveraging data synthesis techniques.

  3. Data sampling techniques: Appropriate sampling techniques will help association efficiently gather a representative subset of data.

  4. Collaborative data sharing: By establishing data sharing agreements or partnerships, Association can access additional datasets that can complement or supplement your own data.

Thus , Using above strategies ,Association can benefit from a larger and more diverse pool of information which will help to analyze data comprehensively and get insights more correctly.

3. Variety:¶

  • Variety refers to the diversity and range of data types, formats, and sources that are used for analysis.

  • In the given data set , we can see there is high amount of correlation between many columns means many columns providing the same information. Ex. Score, BasketScored, BasketGiven etc columns providing the same information. So data set have low level of variety.

To improve variety in data analysis, Association can follow below approaches:¶

  1. Data source diversification: Association can consider incorporating data from external sources, such as public datasets, third-party data providers etc. This can provide access to diverse datasets and perspectives that enrich the analysis.

  2. Unstructured data analysis: This will get from text documents, social media posts, emails, or customer reviews.Association can use techniques, like natural language processing (NLP) or sentiment analysis which will allow Association to tap into valuable information contained within unstructured sources.

  3. Data integration and consolidation: Data integration techniques, like data warehousing or data lakes, can be utilized to bring together diverse data sources and facilitate cross-domain analysis.

  4. Multimedia data analysis:Techniques like image recognition, audio classification, or video processing can be employed to extract insights from multimedia sources.

  5. Sensor data analysis: Sensor data can provide Association real-time information about environmental conditions, equipment performance, or user behavior.

  6. Text analytics and sentiment analysis: Techniques, such as topic modeling or sentiment analysis will help Association to gain insights from textual data.

Thus , by improving the variety of data in data analysis, Association can uncover hidden patterns, trends, or relationships

4. Velocity: ¶

  • Velocity refers to the speed at which data is collected, processed, and analyzed.

  • Such tournaments are arranged world wide in specific seasons , so tracing the respective data from the each tournaments will help to improve the association management predicting capability so association should always give importance to speedily collecting the data and processing.

To improve velocity in data , Association can consider following strategies:¶

  1. Automated data collection: By using web scraping tools etc. to collect data directly will help to reduce manual effort, save time, and ensure a continuous flow of data.

  2. Real-time data processing: For that , Association management can Streaming platforms or event-driven architectures can be employed to process data as it arrives, allowing for immediate insights and responses. It will association to react swiftly to changing conditions and make real time decisions.

  3. Parallel processing and distributed computing: Association management can use technologies like Apache Hadoop or Apache Spark which allow for the distribution of computational tasks across multiple nodes, enabling faster data processing and analysis by harnessing the power of multiple machines.

  4. Preprocessing and data transformation: This can involve using efficient algorithms or techniques to handle missing data, normalize data, or aggregate data.

  5. Cloud computing and scalability: Cloud-based services like Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure etc offers scalability and on-demand resources. This helps for faster data processing and analysis during peak periods.

  6. Data caching and indexing: It will help Association management to improve data retrieval speed.

  7. Data pipeline optimization: This will help Association management to Streamline and optimize the data pipeline to eliminate bottlenecks and reduce processing delays.

Thus by implementing these strategies, Association can improve the velocity of data analysis, enabling faster insights and more timely decision-making.

5.Veracity:¶

  • Veracity means the accuracy , reliability and trustworthiness of the data being analyzed.

Some common challenges related to data veracity includes:¶

  1. Inaccurate or incomplete data
  2. Data bias
  3. Data integrity and security

To address the veracity concerns , Association should implement the following practices:¶

  1. Data validation and cleansing: It will help to identify and correct errors, inconsistencies, and missing values in the dataset.

  2. Data governance:- Association should follow robust data governance policies to establish data quality standards,define data ownership and implement data management policies. This will helps ensure accountability, data quality control, and adherence to regulatory requirements.

  1. Data auditing:- Association should Conduct regular data audits to assess the accuracy, completeness, and consistency of the collected data. This involves evaluating the data against predefined quality metrics and performing checks to identify any potential issues.

  2. Data ethics: Association management should promote ethical considerations in data collection, storage, and analysis.

Thus , by following the above measures , Association can achieve greater confidence in the predictions derived from the data analysis process and make more informed decisions based on trustworthy information.

4. Statistical Analysis: [10 Marks] ¶

A. Is there any significant difference between Funds raised by companies that are still operating vs companies that closed down? [1 Mark] ¶

  • a. Write the null hypothesis.
  • b. Write down alternative hypothesis.
  • c. Test for significance and conclusion.

Ans: ¶

We will see the distribution of the Funds raised by the company with respective to it's Operating and Closed state.¶

In [89]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2)

fig.set_figheight(5)
fig.set_figwidth(15)

sns.distplot(df.loc[df.OperatingState == 'Operating', 'Funds_in_million'], ax = ax[0])
sns.distplot(df.loc[df.OperatingState =='Closed', 'Funds_in_million'], ax = ax[1])

ax[0].set_title('Funds raised by the companies still operating')
ax[1].set_title('Funds raised by companies that got closed')
plt.show()

Observations:¶

  • Distribution of both plot is almost similar . So we can't predict about there significant difference.
  • For that we will have to do the hypothesis test.
  • Since our goal is to compare the difference in means, we will use 2 sample t test or z-test.
  • One important point to notice is that even they don't have normal distribution but our sample size is reasonably big so we can go with it.

B. Write the null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis. [1 Mark]¶

Ans: ¶

Null hypothesis (Ho) : There is no difference between the two means

Alternate hypothesis (Ha) : There is significant difference between the two means

We will follow bellow step to reach at conclusion.¶

Identify test :¶

This problem statement we can solve using the Independent Two Sample T-Test¶

Define null and alternative hypotheses¶

For deciding any significant difference between Funds raised by companies that are still operating vs companies that closed down,

  • the null hypothesis will be the mean of funds raised in million by the Operating company and Closed down company are same.

    $\mu{(Operating)}$ = $\mu{(ClosedDown)}$.

  • And alternative hypothesis will be mean of funds raised in million by the Operating company and Closed down company are different.

$H_0$: $\mu{(Operating)}$ - $\mu{(ClosedDown)}$ = 0 i.e $\mu{(Operating)}$ = $\mu{(ClosedDown)}$

$H_A$: $\mu{(Operating)}$ - $\mu{(ClosedDown)}$ $\neq$ 0 i.e $\mu{(Operating)}$ $\neq$ $\mu{(ClosedDown)}$

Decide the significance level¶

Here we select 𝛼 = 0.05 .¶

Calculate the p - value and test statistic¶

We have TWO INDEPENDET samples of funds in millions of two company so we use the scipy.stats.ttest_ind to calculate the t_test . This function returns t statistic and two-tailed p value.

This is a two-sided test for the null hypothesis that 2 independent samples have identical average (expected) values. This test assumes that the populations have identical variances.

We assume that our population have identical variance. ¶

First , we will use Independent Two Sample T-Test:¶

In [90]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind


sample1 = df.loc[df.OperatingState == 'Operating', 'Funds_in_million']
sample2 = df.loc[df.OperatingState =='Closed', 'Funds_in_million']

alpha = 0.05   # Let's consider a significance level of 5%

test_statistic, p_value = ttest_ind(sample1, sample2)



if p_value <= alpha:
    print(f'Since the p-value, {round(p_value, 3)} < {alpha} (alpha) the difference is significant and we reject the Null hypothesis')
else:
    print(f'''Since the p-value, {round(p_value,3)} > {alpha} (alpha) the difference is not significant and,
    we fail to reject the Null hypothesis''')

Since the p-value, 0.193 > 0.05 (alpha) the difference is not significant and,
    we fail to reject the Null hypothesis

Now , we use z-test:¶

In [91]:
from statsmodels.stats.weightstats import ztest

sample1 = df.loc[df.OperatingState == 'Operating', 'Funds_in_million']
sample2 = df.loc[df.OperatingState =='Closed', 'Funds_in_million']

alpha = 0.05   # Let's consider a significance level of 5%

test_statistic, p_value = ztest(sample1, sample2)

if p_value <= alpha:
    print(f'Since the p-value, {round(p_value, 3)} < {alpha} (alpha) the difference is significant and we reject the Null hypothesis')
else:
    print(f'''Since the p-value, {round(p_value,3)} > {alpha} (alpha) the difference is not significant and,
    we fail to reject the Null hypothesis''')
    

Since the p-value, 0.192 > 0.05 (alpha) the difference is not significant and,
    we fail to reject the Null hypothesis

Thus , sample size is > 30 so both t-test and z-test giving the same result.¶

Conclusion: ¶

Thus from the above t-test and z-test result ,we can conclude that both Operating and Closed down company have the same mean at the 5% significance so we don't have enough evidence to say that the companies that have raised more money tend to succeed more or vice-versa.¶

Ans: ¶

Null hyputhesis (Ho): The proportion of companies that are operating is the same in both categories - winners and contestants

Alternative hypothesis (Ha): The proportion of companies that are operating is significantly different from each other, among the two categories.

In [95]:
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

test_statistic, p_value = proportions_ztest([contestants_operating, winners_operating], [contestants, winners])

print('P_value is: ',p_value)

print('#'*40)
if p_value <= alpha:
    print(f'Since the p-value, {round(p_value, 3)} < {alpha} (alpha) the difference is significant and we reject the Null hypothesis')
else:

    \t we fail to reject the Null hypothesis''')
